This ode was composed on the anniversary of Horace’s accident with the tree (C. ii. 13), and is supposed by Franke (p. 158, sqq.) to have been written A.u.c. 729. His argument is very long, and rests chiefly on the allusions in the fifth and sixth stanzas. The Parthians were invaded that year by a Scythian army to restore Phraates (C. i. 26, Introduction). In that year Augustus brought to an end his expedition against the Cantabri (C. 4, Introduction), and during his absence he assumes that Maecenas was governor of the city, as he had been on former occasions (Tac. Anu. vi. 11). He places in that year the expedition of Lentulus against the tribes of the Danube (C. ii. 9. 23), here represented by the Dacian king Cotison.
